segments.text: date and place of birth wilfred bruce truax i was born october 15 1922 in donna texas i went through school except for the fifth grade all of it there in donna the fifth grade i spent one semester in wisconsin
and one semester in Waco, Texas.
This had come about primarily because our house had burned that summer before.
Was this a fire of natural origin?
No, it came about, my dad was always experimenting and trying to improve things around the house.
He was trying to get a water heater working and there was an explosion.
He was out in the yard at the time of the explosion, but it apparently scattered fuel pretty good because by the time he turned around, the whole house was on fire.
This must have been a fairly unsettling experience for the family.
Did y'all lose all your possessions?
Almost entirely.
My dad got back in as far as the kitchen and the only two things I can remember is he pulled the drawer of the ordinary silverware we used and also carried out the electric cooker that we had.
Other than that, why, and then of course a little bit of salvage of

few pictures and this where they were in a deep stack that it have burned edges but not completely burned up and but nearly everything else this was of course in the depression 33 and it was amazing how good people were to us we
took us in at various places.
We stayed and what have you.
Well, I think each of the kids' classes, I know mine specifically did, they all brought various things from home or knew.
You feel that people took care of each other more then than they do now?
I tend to believe this in a sense.
Of course you got to keep in mind too though that this is the difference of a town of 3,000 against living in 150, 200,000 city.
Everybody tended to be a little closer probably and know each other's problems more and
This probably couldn't have happened really at a worse time during the deep part of the Depression.
What was your father's occupation?
As far back as I could remember, he was in the electrical business.
At this particular time, he was working for David Wilson, an electrical contractor there in town.
After we came back from Wisconsin and Waco, he went into business for himself.
I see.
And could you give us your dad's name?
My dad was Tuxton Burrell Truax.
Remember where he grew up?
He grew up primarily out at Novice, which is about 15, 18 miles west of Coleman.
And your mother, can you remember her name and where she grew up?
My mother was...
Ada Buckmaster, she grew up primarily in Wisconsin.
She and dad met in New Mexico, where she was teaching school.
But her father was a doctor and one time was head of the state and St. Asylum institution there in Wisconsin.
I take it then your mother was fairly uneducated when
Yes, she was.
It's a little interesting that their 50th wedding anniversary, I met a man who, in New Mexico, she had had as a pupil, that they had just by accident run in there.
He heard the clerk mention the name Truax in the grocery store.
And this was, he remembered.
my mother and renewed an acquaintance.
Did your mother go to college?
She did?
I'm sure she did, but I'm really not this sure where.
At Janesville, I think, but I'm not this positive.
Well, when did you graduate from high school?
I graduated from Donna High School in 1940.
Do you remember anything about the high school there?
The size?
I believe, if I remember right, there were 320 in high school, and I believe there were 39 or 40 in our graduating class.
Do you remember anything about your high school experiences, anything that comes to mind at that time?
It might give some bearing on the education at that time.
No, not really.
We had just primarily one teacher to a subject type thing, and there was one or two of them.
They'd always done real well in math in high school, and when I got to A&M, why, I decided that it was only because it had been so easy.
And where chemistry, at that time at least, was considered kind of a bust-out course, I made B's in it because of a good foundation from a good instructor.
You felt you were fairly well prepared then to enter college, then, from your grades?
Yes, I was probably third or fourth in our high school class.
As a freshman, I had
the highest grades in the class.
How did you wind up going to A&M?
What motivated you to go there?
I think primarily my father.
I can't ever really recall him ever talking specifically about it, except that somewhere or another he had me convinced I wanted to go to college.
I grew up working with him even before he went into business for himself, weekends and such as this.
He was always one of great patience and would answer any kind of questions or what have you.
And like I say, he had not even finished
Well, I'm not sure how far he got, but I know he didn't finish high school, and I'm not sure he ever got to high school.
And this was one of the things that he made every effort to convince me that I wanted to in a roundabout way, not pressuring you or the way that you
would rebel and not want to go.
I can remember writing themes in Spanish about wanting to go to A&M, major in engineering, and go to South America.
Traveling in the service took the South America desire out some.
However, I always liked traveling.
What were your first impressions?
First of all, when did you arrive at A&M, and what were your first impressions?
Well, this is, I'm sure, in one sense, some different.
Boy, at one time, my dad went to a short course with an Alton Bird, who lived there in Donner still, but long years ago, before I can remember, they were in
an auto shop business together.
And we went to, they went to a short course, and I went up there with them.
And their son was, Mr. Bird's son was in college at that time.
And immediately after I graduated from high school, that week following, I hitchhiked up there and spent a week with George Bird just before his graduation.

In a sense, this was, well, it didn't have any real repercussions in that Burt Campbell, who was orderly for George as a freshman and George a senior, made up my bed, took me to breakfast meals and this sort of thing,
When then in the following year I'm in the same company with Burt Campbell as a sophomore and me as an incoming freshman.
I see.
And when did, what did you start in the fall of 1940?
In the fall of 1940.
I see.
I entered.
What company?
In headquarters signal company.
And what was your major at this point?
Electrical engineering.
Electrical engineering.
What do you remember from your freshman year?
Was it particularly hard on you?
Was the hazing severe?

I'd always looked at the hazing a little different I guess than than lots in the they it appeared a good deal to me as far as you taking care of an upperclassman's room for a year and you get your room taken care of for three years and
It seems like a good trade.
Yeah, this is...
I got caught eating cake when you shouldn't have and drank the castor oil and ate spinach.
And, of course, I can remember trying to haze me drinking buttermilk, but I like buttermilk and I like spinach, so lots of these things didn't bother me like some of them.
The chew in the back, I got sick.
The hazing though was not particularly physical at this time.
No, it was very physical much of the time.
Of course the sophomores,
were running it.

The one thing that to me broke down later, and I often wondered if this is when they started going straight through and it wasn't that period between the end of your sophomore year and the beginning of the junior year and this, that they didn't want to quit.
But as a freshman,
In our company, at least, it was very resonant.
Specifically, a senior could call for a freshman, and all freshmen could come running.
A junior could call fish so-and-so, and that freshman would come running.
A sophomore had to go get him a freshman if he wanted a detailed run.
One of the worst things you could do would be not to speak to and or go meet friends of a senior.
He didn't ever say anything to you, but he got him a junior and that junior got in several sophomores and the sophomores got all were freshmen.
So that it was a strict type of chain of command, so to speak.
Do you feel later why this seemed to break down and the juniors and seniors were hazing just as much as the sophomores were?
Do you feel that the seniors or juniors kept the hazing in line?
Did the sophomores do most of the physical hazing?
Yes, the sophomores primarily did.
Well, before the first football game, the company commander announced there would be a company meeting at the second floor in the hall there.
With it, they lined up with boards, and the juniors went through, and the sophomores went through, and the freshmen went through, and they went on to football games.
And then juniors lined up, and sophomores went through, and the freshmen went through, and they went on, and then the sophomores lined up.
But primarily, the seniors and the juniors were the ones who controlled it, but they didn't do the hazing.
And I say they didn't do the hazing.
Some freshmen got real out of line.
A senior would collar in a couple of juniors, and those juniors in turn
that same chain of command to the sophomores.
And the sophomores would have the whole freshman class in our company there.
Keep in mind, though, that they did have some, in a sense, reverse outlets.
Halloween night, the juniors came around and got the freshmen.
And we out and dug a mud hole.
And sophomores were free game then in our class.
And they were hauled out and dumped

the mud hole and it was it was not gentle to say the least they could fight and look there were always more freshmen than there were same way we'd have semi-controlled i guess you would say tackle football games with just towels for padding and that's all so that you did have some in a sense uh
semi-legal opportunities to vent your anger at the sophomores, and yet the system still worked.
Do you feel like you learned anything from this particular discipline, shall we call it?
Do you feel like there was anything to be learned from this, that there was a point to it?
I always felt that this was
was one part of that that made you closer as a unit through your years there.
Because almost, except for rare exceptions, and we had a couple who just delighted in hazing, I guess you'd say.
But primarily, it was the chain of command type thing and not just indiscriminately.
Hazing for hazing.
Right.
Now, I'm not sure that this is true on the whole campus by any means.
I think that there are some of the other places where maybe it was a difference in the group.
All of them, of course, in the Signal Corps at least started out.
signed up for EE.
They didn't all necessarily stay there all the way through, but this was the way you ended up in the Signal Corps to begin with.
I see.
Do you feel that maybe this taught you self-discipline in a way?
Could it teach you to discipline yourself as far as having to follow certain rules and regulations?
There were places you were supposed to be at certain times and things you did at certain times and things you did not do.
Do you feel this way?
I felt very definitely that it did.
And it also
The hazing bit was controlled, the study, and this is one of the places some of the stories you heard make you think then that it wasn't as controlled as some of the other units.
Seven o'clock, call the quarters, you got at your desk and you stayed at your desk even if you had to
prop your head up until 11 o'clock.
The only place you could go would be to the restroom and back to your room, and that was it.
You didn't go visit any other freshmen anywhere.
You stayed in your room and were supposed to study.
There was no time that any of the upperclassmen interfered with this study time, sending you on details or anything else.
I gathered that this, as I said, didn't necessarily hold true to all the other units.
Do you think this taught you how to study?
How to discipline your time?
Not really, but it was if you went ahead and used it, why it helped.
And there was at 11 o'clock you went to bed, however
I don't know if there was a specific time, but I've been up as early as 3 o'clock working on a drawing or something like this.
And there never seemed to be a limit at what time you could get back up again.
But you did go to bed at 11 o'clock and lights out.
I see.
Do you remember anything else about your freshman year?
Any of the courses that were particularly hard?
Well, primarily, of course, I did standard engineering, freshman engineering.
curriculum.
Trig, as I mentioned before, after I got up there, I'm not that sure of my math background since I don't remember ever having heard of Trig before I went to college.
And the math, I guess, primarily was where I had my hardest time as a sophomore year

busting the first semester I guess the second semester first semester of calculus is the only course I ever busted but did you lose a lot of people that first year out of your freshman class a lot as I don't remember exactly how many we started with in the company but there were somewhere 28 or 30 would be my
recollection and as I recall we end up with something like 12 and this included the end of our freshman year included a couple of frogs midterm transfers.
As you went along are there any particular professors that you have that you remember that you think might have helped you or been inspirational?
who maybe took particular pains with you, or any that you had a close relationship that you recall?
I would think in the EE department, of course, LL Four Acre was probably one that, don't know if it's necessarily inspiration, but more understanding of some of your problems and this and
than any I had, and I had him, I guess, as sophomore and junior on some courses.
You, in the department at that time, of course, Rhodey was one who was, always amazed you.
He could ride around the room about three times during a one-hour class.
Let's get back a little bit.
Do you remember any impressions about the campus when you got there?
What you felt about the whole physical nature of it?
Was it over, was it friendly?
Or was it a stark sort of place?
No, it was, of course, we lived in, at that time, the new dorms, the 1 to 12.
I'd always thought that the campus was well landscaped and they changed it with the seasons.
It was always to me a thrill, so to speak, hitchhiking back and
come in the East Gate, it was a long ways back up to the norm area, but even so, it was a sense of being home, so to speak.
You mentioned hitchhiking.
Did most of the students hitchhike?
There were a tremendous number, I would say, hitchhiked.
As I recall, there wasn't anybody in our company had a car on the campus.
when I was a freshman, and I could be mistaken about some of the...
Were you allowed cars if you had one at this time?
There were a few cars on the campus.
Whether this was because of a disability or what, this was never my worry since it was all I could do to stay there.
How did you finance your education?
Did your father help you?
Did you work any?
Primarily my father.
I mean, I worked for him all the time at no wages, so to speak, and this part of it.
Oh, at one time I did wait tables some in the mess hall.
Steve, was this before or after the war?
We'll get to the war in a minute.
I believe this was probably after the war had started, but before I'd gone on active duty.
Okay, we'll get to that in a minute.
Is there anything else you remember about these pre-war days at A&M?
Oh, we were talking about the discipline, the regimentation, so to speak.
Obviously, it all agreed with me since when I started as a
Freshman, I weighed 130 pounds, and at Easter, I weighed 168.
How was the food?
Excellent.
It was very good.
Yes.
You got enough to eat?
No question about it.
It was family style.
Were you eating a Dunkin' at this time?
A Dunkin'.
Mm-hmm.
As a freshman, did you have any trouble eating?
Did they give you any harassment about...
No, as I said a while ago, sometimes they would feel like they were hazing you to make you eat spinach or make you drink buttermilk or some of these things.
That's no problem.
Some, right, this was, I got my fill of turnip greens one time and it took years to ever eat them again, but other than that, I know
Did they ever stop you from eating certain things?
Did they say, you know, y'all can't have this tonight?
Only dessert, and this was, of course, we used to get out every morning, 6 o'clock or whenever it was, so many days left till Kush, eating dessert.
And anybody asked and gave the wrong day while you started all over, so we almost, I don't recall that we ever worked down to where
This was legal.
So this went on pretty much your entire freshman year?
Yes.
But it didn't hurt you any?
No, not.
They weren't depriving you of enough food to keep you alive.
You were there when war was declared in December of 1941.
Can you remember the mood of the campus when war was declared, the feeling?
Well, I recall that Sunday afternoon, specifically, everybody in a sense kind of hushed homes and shocked and amazed.
There was a feeling of disbelief then?
Well, in a sense, yes.
However, they had already started this where you belong to the enlisted reserve before you
could participate in advanced ROTC and this sort of thing.
As I recall, I had gotten my papers because this was, of course, then in my sophomore year and you were to do this before
at the end of the school term so you would be ready the following year for consideration of advanced ROTC.
I see.
Was it advanced ROTC at this time, was it difficult to get into?
Were they very selective?
No.
As I recall, most who wanted it got in.
It may not have been quite that easy, I'm not real sure.
Now, war was declared when you were a sophomore at this time.
Probably toward the end of the semester.
Well, toward the end of the first semester of the sophomore year.
Now, what happened after war was declared?
What went on on the campus?
Do you remember what preparations were made, gearing up for wartime activities?
The only big change that I can recall at this particular time was
change in the ROTC instructors took place more rapidly.
And as I recall, they were thinned down to a certain extent also.
But this took place over a period of time.
As a freshman and sophomore, we had
A man who was a staff sergeant who received a direct commission, and as a captain, and with his longevity and kids, was about the second highest paid military personnel on the campus.
How long did it take him to get rolling?
Did the second semester go smoothly, or did they interrupt you at any time during the second semester?
No, I recall no interruptions.
So you went on through your sophomore year?
I went through and finished my sophomore year, and actually this is when then they started going straight through three semesters a year.
And my finances being what they were, I laid out and worked that summer here in Corpus Christi and went back in the fall.
And on this basis then, you didn't start.
advanced ROTC at mid-turn, so I was actually then in December or approximately before I rejoined an ROTC unit.
I lived in Goodwin Hall, I guess it was.
As a civilian student?
Yes.
Did you have to wear a uniform?
We still wore a uniform, but we were not in the
Corps as such.
So you were getting ahead academically ahead of your military then?
Right.
So then in the mid- then what was not mid-semester, when did you rejoin a unit now?
Well actually it would be the beginning of my academic senior year, but it turned out it was my junior year.
And then it was in this semester when we
all went on active duty, all those who were in advanced ROTC.
The units all left the campus for approximately a week, as I recall.
Do you remember when this was?
Approximately what day was it?
March.
March of 43.
As mentioned before, you
To be an advanced ROTC, you had to be an enlisted reserve, and this was a matter of calling up the enlisted reserve.
I see.
From A&M, units went various places.
In the Signal Corps, we went to Camp Beauregard, Louisiana.
There were those who went to Camp Walters.
those went to Fort Sam Houston.
These were all induction centers.
Where did you go?
I went to Beauregard, Louisiana.
For how long?
It took about a week.
We went through the standard battery of tests and were issued in uniforms and taken down to Camp Livingston for inoculations, and then
put on a train back to the campus and we finished our regular semester.
Were you on active duty and being paid?
Yes.
The whole time?
Just after we were called active duty.
And what rank did they consider you all as?
As a private.
As a private, and they were paying you all as private?
Right.
I see.
Okay, after you came back to the campus, you went ahead and finished that semester?
We finished our regular classes that semester and immediately after
at the end of the term scattered to the winds again.
Those, and here again I'm talking now not class of 44, because I, in this ROTC business, I was really with the class of 45, having missed a year of ROTC.
But all of these in this class went to various
training camps for basic training before going to OCS.
Those who were actually in the class of 44 went directly, and I say directly, almost directly to OCS, I believe.
What camp did you go to?
There was a train load of us.
We first went to Fort Sam, and then from there on a train to Camp Roberts, California.
As the story goes, I wasn't there, but supposedly some of them working in the supply room, the colonel came in and said, boy, there's been a mistake made.
All of y'all are not supposed to have been here.
Those of us there at the time were cavalry, Coast Guard cavalry, no, no field artillery.
Calvary, Coast Artillery, Engineers, Signal Corps, and Infantry.
And almost immediately, those of us that had been in Signal Corps over D.C. went to Camp Kohler close to Sacramento.
The Coast Artillery went to Camp McQuaid, and the Engineers went on up to Camp Abbott in Oregon.
And this was basic training?
This was basic training.
and was probably some of the best military training I ever had, and the company commander got out, y'all are ROTC, you're supposed to be able to know how to march, let's see.
We marched, and he said, there's no sense in spending time on that, we'll go to something else.
Fortunately, we went to Camp Kohler, they had a,
training program set up, and we were doing things that we had done the first six weeks.
We were in freshman ROTC.
Did they keep the A&M people together?
We stayed together, yes.
You didn't have any people coming in from the outside?
We had a few, and really you feel sorry for them because they were behind.
Some of them, right.
We had one or two draftees there at
at Camp Roberts that were in a unit with, well, it was a whole battalion, training battalion, full of nothing but Aggies.
So there was no way that they could do it.
And eventually, as I recall, they got them transferred out.
How long were you in basic training?
Until September, I believe it was, October.
It was supposedly the pretty much standard basic training.
Do you remember how many weeks?
Not for positive.
It was about the middle of July when we went to Camp Kohler after having been there at Camp Roberts for about six weeks.
I see.
Somewhere about the first of October, we were assigned to an ASTP unit.
We were sent back to A&M to be in the ASTP.
What's an ASTP unit?
Army Student Training Unit Program.
Okay.
You were sent back to the State College?
Still as a group.
I was presumed primarily because there wasn't an opening in OCS because after one semester of this we did go on to OCS.
Now wait a minute, so you were back at A&M for another full semester then?
For, right, it was a speeded up and these were, we ended up getting some hours credit just as a
transcript shows full military referral ROTC credit by having gotten a commission.
These hours were added to just as if you'd taken them there at A&M.
Now, wait a minute.
You're talking about getting a commission.
After basic training, you still were not commissioned, were you?
No.
No.
We went to the STP unit.
Then from there, we went to Fort Monmouth, New Jersey to Signal Corps.
Do you remember when this was?
We went in February, right towards the end of February, and this was quite a change weather-wise.
And it still has a unit to OCS?
All of us in the Signal Corps, yes.
The other units were going various directions, and I'm not positive that all of them came back.
A number of the various different ones did come back.
But I can't be positive about all of them coming to ASTP before they went to OCS.
I know the group that I was with in the Signal Corps did.
So you were at OCS for how long?
I got out of OCS in June.
Now your A&M training and all the other military training, did you have any trouble with OCS?
No, not particularly.
Were all the people here, your OCS training unit, were they A&M people?
No, all of those of us in the ROTC were in this class, but there were some other classes.
I don't remember ever seeing Mr. Foraker afterwards this.
but one experience that I recall well was there was a group from Clemson, and they were talking about one of their prof and imitating him, and they said, well, that sounds like Four Acre.
Well, it is Four Acre.
It was my understanding that it was Four Acre's either twin brother or brother, but there were these from Clemson.
There were a few
from regular Army enlisted personnel that were there at OCS class, but primarily it was the two largest groups in our class, I think, were Clemson ROTC and A&M ROTC units.
How did A&M ROTC units at this time stack up against the other schools?
I think we did probably pretty close to equally well.
We had
I had two pretty close friends that busted out.
The big problem primarily was barracks inspection while you were at class and having the closing button or some such thing as this and even work out trying to
help and check them and that kind of thing and you'd get down for formation to go to class and they'd forgotten something and run back up and mess up something in their hurry and this sort of thing.
The A&M people pretty much stick together over this then?
Yes.
Try to help one another through.
Yes.
So you got out of OCS in June?
I believe this is right in June.
Then you were commissioned at that point?
At that point, commissioned, yes.
Then what?
I went to officer school for about six weeks.
It was called Long Lines Inside, which is telephone equipment, switchboards, teletype, repeaters, this sort of equipment, and then was assigned to a unit.
This was also at Fort Monmouth.
and then was assigned to a casual detachment group that went overseas withSignal Corps had what they called teams in this group that went over.
There were ten radio teams and five switchboard teams.
Okay, let me stop just for a second here and turn my tape over.
